00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:55.780
not a fan of Donald Trump,
supported by MoveOn.org,

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:59.070
and that he had been
linked to the Islamic state.

00:09:59.070 --> 00:10:00.390
All of which was untrue.

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:05.620 position:56%
None of this stuff is accurate, but
it was out there and had been passed

00:10:05.620 --> 00:10:09.730
on through the algorithms of
Facebook and Google to many,

00:10:09.730 --> 00:10:16.300
many unsuspecting recipients
of these platforms.

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:20.620
And Facebook has other problems,
as you no doubt have been aware.

00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:22.520
I mean it's not just
a fake news problem,

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:27.530
but fake ads have circulated on
Facebook, including those linked

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:31.480
to accounts linked to Russia

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:35.780
over the past several months during
the presidential campaign last year

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:38.170
and in to this year as well.

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:41.350
So Facebook and Google in
particular have problems in terms

00:10:41.350 --> 00:10:44.780
of letting algorithms
drive their content,

00:10:44.780 --> 00:10:50.100
what appears on their
platforms, on their newsfeeds.

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:53.190
And this is no minor issue.

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:55.020
This is no minor problem.

00:10:55.020 --> 00:10:58.150
And it's hard to see how Facebook
and Google can let this go

00:10:58.150 --> 00:11:02.520
on without -- by just allowing
algorithms to drive content.

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:05.410
And that's essentially
where we are now.

00:11:05.410 --> 00:11:11.550
So anything, almost anything, wild
stuff, phony ads, can get up there

00:11:11.550 --> 00:11:14.300
and reach incredible
numbers of people.

00:11:14.300 --> 00:11:18.330
Because these platforms, two-thirds
of American adults every day log

00:11:18.330 --> 00:11:21.500
in to social media of one
kind or another for news.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:27.060
So this is a serious issue in terms
of undercutting popular discourse.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:31.020
One thing I will say
about fake news, though.

00:11:31.020 --> 00:11:33.510
It's not new.

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:38.960
We have dealt with fake
news for many years.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:43.420
Perhaps not with the intensity
that algorithms transmit news

00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:45.250 position:56%
to newsfeeds at Facebook and Google,

00:11:45.250 --> 00:11:46.880
but nonetheless it
has been out there.

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:48.610
It has circulated.

00:11:48.610 --> 00:11:51.700
For example, the "New
York Sun" in August

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:57.710
of 1835 published a six part
series in which it reported,

00:11:57.710 --> 00:11:59.690
this penny newspaper
in New York City --

00:11:59.690 --> 00:12:05.010
reported that there was
life found on the moon.

00:12:05.010 --> 00:12:09.390
And that the lunar landscape was
populated by exotic animals as well

00:12:09.390 --> 00:12:14.550
as bat wing humanoid characters.

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:21.130
The "New York Sun's"
ostensible source

00:12:21.130 --> 00:12:25.450
for this reporting was the work of
an astronomer named John Herschel

00:12:25.450 --> 00:12:28.020
who was reporting from the southern
hemisphere that had been able

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:30.900
to see these objects
on the lunar surface.

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:33.950
Even to the degree of being
able to determine the gender

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:38.350
of these winged humanoid figures.

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:43.940
The "New York Sun," 1835.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:48.920
Later in the 19th century in 1897 a

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:52.700
"New York Herald" reporter named
George Bronson Rea published a book

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:56.180 position:56%
called "Facts and Fakes About Cuba."

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:58.310
"Facts and Fakes About Cuba."

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:03.690 position:56%
And he was lamenting, this reporter,
he was lamenting the circulation

00:13:03.690 --> 00:13:10.000
of fakes, fake news, about the
Cuban insurrection that led in 1898

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.220
to the Spanish American War.

00:13:12.220 --> 00:13:16.300
And he was complaining and laid
out his case in a book that came

00:13:16.300 --> 00:13:19.740
out in early 1897 about
the correspondence

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:22.360
for New York newspapers
as well as others who were

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:26.770
out there peddling this
garbage, this made up stuff,

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:32.560
these extreme stories about
Spanish atrocities on Cuba.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:35.490
Intended, he thought, to whip
up public sentiment at home

00:13:35.490 --> 00:13:38.600
in the United States to
support U.S. intervention

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:43.360
in the war for Cuban independence.

00:13:43.360 --> 00:13:46.380 position:56%
That's what happened, but not
because of news content necessarily.

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:48.740
It's because of other
factors that diplomatic clash

00:13:48.740 --> 00:13:52.600
between the United States, Cuba,
and Spain, the colonial rulers,

00:13:52.600 --> 00:13:55.600
and that's what led in
1898, April of 1898,

00:13:55.600 --> 00:13:57.470
to the Spanish American War.

00:13:57.470 --> 00:14:02.040
But the point here is that fakes
and facts had been long disputed,

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:06.020
and had been long a subject
in American journalism.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:08.300
Now one problem with fake news

00:14:08.300 --> 00:14:13.000
in the contemporary context
is what do we mean by this.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.270
What do we mean?

00:14:15.270 --> 00:14:17.880
It's a term that's proven
very flexible, very fluid.

00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:19.820
In fact, so fluid that the

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:23.170
"Washington Post's" media
writer Margaret Sullivan came

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:26.340 position:56%
