00:15:40.390 --> 00:15:42.110
You know, demonstrable not true.

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:45.580
I mean a lot of photographs
suggested that, you know,

00:15:45.580 --> 00:15:48.770
there was a pretty thin turnout
in the streets of Washington

00:15:48.770 --> 00:15:50.070
for Trump's inauguration.

00:15:50.070 --> 00:15:53.470
But nonetheless it just
is emblematic of his use

00:15:53.470 --> 00:15:59.100
of exaggeration, hyperbole,
falsehoods,

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:00.640
to push an agenda, I suppose.

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:01.940
His own agenda.

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:05.090
He's very narcissistic.

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:08.720
Anyway, he has made
great use of fake news,

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:11.680
and is one of the reasons why the

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:16.130
"Washington Post" suggested
we bury this term.

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:17.940
But it's out there.

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:21.320
And again the definitions are
very difficult to pin down.

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:25.580
The online site Vox says that
false news -- Defines it this way.

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:29.010
False news claims are presented
in an official looking way,

00:16:29.010 --> 00:16:31.680
often online, and in a way to --

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:36.770
that's intended to deceive
readers, intended to deceive.

00:16:36.770 --> 00:16:39.560
The "Post" has said
it defined fake news

00:16:39.560 --> 00:16:44.780
as deliberately constructed lies
in the form of news articles

00:16:44.780 --> 00:16:47.150
that are meant to mislead
the public.

00:16:47.150 --> 00:16:51.550 position:56%
So you see both of these definitions
include a sense of intention.

00:16:51.550 --> 00:16:54.340
Intentionality.

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:58.610
Now I would offer a definition
that sort of takes us away

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:03.080
from intentionality and just
embraces everything that is false,

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:09.520
erroneous, dubious, media driven
tales that circulate widely

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:13.890
and serve to corrupt or
warp popular discourse.

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:17.990
And, as we can see from the
examples I mentioned earlier,

00:17:17.990 --> 00:17:20.030
that's exactly what fake news does.

00:17:20.030 --> 00:17:23.660
It corrupts and warps
popular discourse.

00:17:23.660 --> 00:17:27.110
Now my definition has
these advantages.

00:17:27.110 --> 00:17:29.510
It removes intent which can
be very difficult to prove.

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:31.750
How do you know what's
going on inside the mind

00:17:31.750 --> 00:17:34.900
of somebody who's intentionally
or not putting

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:37.090
out erroneous information?

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:39.160
So we just get rid of intent.

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:42.940
It also recognizes that there
is this potential warping

00:17:42.940 --> 00:17:46.100
or corrupting effect of fake news.

00:17:46.100 --> 00:17:48.110
A serious problem, in my view.

00:17:48.110 --> 00:17:51.380 position:56%
And thirdly, this definition insists

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:54.080
that this is not just
a social media problem.

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:56.520
This is not just a
problem of the internet

00:17:56.520 --> 00:17:59.920
and its far out there fringes.

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:02.330 position:56%
This also includes mainstream media.

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:08.460
It is far more than just -- Fake
news is far more than just postings

00:18:08.460 --> 00:18:13.770
at obscure websites on the
fringes of the online world.

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:24.690 position:56%
In fact, the news media these days
are widely distrusted for an ability

00:18:24.690 --> 00:18:28.740
to present news in a fair
minded and accurate fashion.

00:18:28.740 --> 00:18:32.230
And you can see from this
chart these are Gallup polls

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:35.250
that go back 40 plus years.

00:18:35.250 --> 00:18:36.670
And what is shown here goes back

00:18:36.670 --> 00:18:42.680
about 20 showing how popular
recognition of the trust

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:45.190
in the media has subsided,
has eased down,

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:50.390
has ebbed consistently
since the late 1990s.

00:18:50.390 --> 00:18:56.210
And has reached a low during the
presidential campaign of 2016.

00:18:56.210 --> 00:18:59.660
Less than one-third of
American adults responding

00:18:59.660 --> 00:19:04.130
to the survey found
that the news media --

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:06.830
They could have a great deal
or a fair amount of trust

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:10.780
in what the news media
were reporting.

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:13.690
So I submit that fake news
includes, and should include --

00:19:13.690 --> 00:19:17.100
A discussion of fake news should
include mainstream news media

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:18.400
as well.

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:23.810
And the media do have a
trust problem, as we can see.

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:28.480
And there are a number of examples
of mainstream media putting

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:35.920 position:56%
out stories that had to be retracted
or walked back or modified.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:40.650
These are dubious tales that
corrupt the popular discourse.

00:19:40.650 --> 00:19:43.880
And would meet my definition
of fake news.

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:47.460
The first one there is from the
