00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:00.290
Watergate.

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:07.640
That the dogged reporters of Bob
Woodward and Carl Bernstein for the

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:12.790
"Washington Post" uncovered the
evidence that forced Richard Nixon

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:15.210
to resign the presidency.

00:23:15.210 --> 00:23:18.350
This is the dominant
narrative of Watergate.

00:23:18.350 --> 00:23:20.160
You find this everywhere.

00:23:20.160 --> 00:23:22.820
It's in journalism textbooks.

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:25.270
It's in the popular media.

00:23:25.270 --> 00:23:31.030
It's a shorthand version of
what this scandal was all about.

00:23:31.030 --> 00:23:34.120
And it is derived from
in part Woodward

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:36.590
and Bernstein's very
successful book that came

00:23:36.590 --> 00:23:42.100
out just months before Richard
Nixon resigned in August of '74.

00:23:42.100 --> 00:23:45.240
Based also on the very
successful film

00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:48.070
that they -- based on their book.

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:49.370
Same title.

00:23:49.370 --> 00:23:51.480
"All the President's Men"
that came out in 1976.

00:23:51.480 --> 00:23:56.730
And also based on the 20 or
so year long guessing game,

00:23:56.730 --> 00:23:59.980
more like 30 year guessing
game, about the identity

00:23:59.980 --> 00:24:02.050
of the super secret source

00:24:02.050 --> 00:24:06.590
that Woodward had whom was
identified only in the book

00:24:06.590 --> 00:24:09.190
and movie as Deep Throat.

00:24:09.190 --> 00:24:13.810
Turned out to be Mark Felt, number
two at the FBI, who was the subject

00:24:13.810 --> 00:24:17.990
of a movie now that's just out
these days called "Mark Felt:

00:24:17.990 --> 00:24:19.640
The Man Who Took Down
the White House."

00:24:19.640 --> 00:24:22.310
The reviews have been
pretty terrible,

00:24:22.310 --> 00:24:26.140
