00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:33.640
that it must be remembered
that Nixon got Nixon.

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:35.970 position:56%
It wasn't the "Post" that got Nixon.

00:25:35.970 --> 00:25:39.710
And he's referring here to
the secret White House tapes

00:25:39.710 --> 00:25:43.720
that Richard Nixon made of most
conversations in the Oval Office

00:25:43.720 --> 00:25:49.640
between 1971 and '73, tapes that
captured him approving a plan

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:54.180
to divert the investigation
in to the Watergate break in.

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:56.120
Clear obstruction of
justice that led

00:25:56.120 --> 00:26:00.200
to his resignation
in August of 1974.

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:02.880
Nixon got Nixon.

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:04.180
The "Post" didn't get Nixon.

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:06.240
According to Ben Bradley.

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:10.910
And Bob Woodward, in Earth year
terms, has said somewhat the same.

00:26:10.910 --> 00:26:16.270
"To say that the press brought
down Nixon, that's horse poop."

00:26:16.270 --> 00:26:19.920
I think that's what those are for.

00:26:19.920 --> 00:26:25.750
Anyway, he is -- He
too has been adamant

00:26:25.750 --> 00:26:30.930
about this heroic journalist
interpretation being a wrong headed

00:26:30.930 --> 00:26:32.870
interpretation of Watergate.

00:26:32.870 --> 00:26:36.760
And I think the ombudsman
for the "Post" back at the 10

00:26:36.760 --> 00:26:40.190
or 12 years ago, a great guy by
the name of Michael Getler --

00:26:40.190 --> 00:26:46.090
He was ombudsman after that
for PBS for a number of years.

00:26:46.090 --> 00:26:49.590
Getler captured it correctly,
that it was not the "Post,"

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:54.340
but it was the FBI [inaudible]
acting in bipartisan fashion,

00:26:54.340 --> 00:26:58.180
and the courts, that brought down
the Richard Nixon administration.

00:26:58.180 --> 00:26:59.480
It wasn't the "Post."

00:26:59.480 --> 00:27:00.780
And I think that was quite right.

00:27:00.780 --> 00:27:03.190
Because to roll up a
scandal of the dimensions

00:27:03.190 --> 00:27:06.470
of Watergate required
the collective,

00:27:06.470 --> 00:27:10.260
if not always the coordinated
efforts, of many forces

00:27:10.260 --> 00:27:14.300
and factors including special
prosecutors, federal judges,

00:27:14.300 --> 00:27:19.940 position:56%
both houses of Congress, the Supreme
Court, Justice Department, and FBI.

00:27:19.940 --> 00:27:23.070
And even then, even then
with all these forces arrayed

00:27:23.070 --> 00:27:25.830
against Richard Nixon,
he would have walked,

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:27.860
he would have survived
the Watergate scandal,

00:27:27.860 --> 00:27:29.750
had it not been for those tapes.

00:27:29.750 --> 00:27:32.170
Had it not been for
the clear cut evidence

00:27:32.170 --> 00:27:37.040
that showed Nixon was culpable
of obstructing justice.

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:40.020
It needed that kind
of certain evidence

00:27:40.020 --> 00:27:43.640
to dynamite the president
from the Oval Office.

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:49.040 position:56%
He resigned in August of '74 before
he could be impeached and convicted.

00:27:49.040 --> 00:27:51.670
He certainly would have been both.

00:27:51.670 --> 00:27:55.450
So why does this interpretation,
this media myth

00:27:55.450 --> 00:27:59.690
of the heroic journalist,
why does this live on?

00:27:59.690 --> 00:28:01.390
Why does this persist?

00:28:01.390 --> 00:28:03.760
Why is it the dominant narrative?

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:06.290
At least three reasons.

00:28:06.290 --> 00:28:08.800
It's convenient shorthand

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:12.790
for explaining the
Watergate scandal nowadays.

00:28:12.790 --> 00:28:15.070
It's been 45 years
since the burglary

00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:18.730 position:56%
at the Democratic National
Headquarters, and there's been a lot

00:28:18.730 --> 00:28:23.440
that happened during those 2 and a
half years of the Watergate period.

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:26.300
Who was doing what, and
where, and who was Haldeman,

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:27.830
who was Mitchell, who
were all these guys?

00:28:27.830 --> 00:28:31.620
It's -- It was hard to keep
it straight at the time.

00:28:31.620 --> 00:28:35.320
It's impossible to keep
it straight these days.

00:28:35.320 --> 00:28:40.000
So what we have as the dominant
narrative is a simplified easily

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:46.520 position:56%
accessible shorthand that explains
Watergate, that embraces the essence

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:49.500
of the scandal, I.E.
Richard Nixon resigned,

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:54.170
but adds a little media
centric window dressing to it.

00:28:54.170 --> 00:28:57.920
That it was because of these
dogged intrepid reporters

00:28:57.920 --> 00:29:01.510
that Richard Nixon lost his office.

00:29:01.510 --> 00:29:03.400
Easy to explain.

00:29:03.400 --> 00:29:05.300
It's convenient.

00:29:05.300 --> 00:29:07.940
It's simplistic.

00:29:07.940 --> 00:29:09.620
It avoids the complexities

00:29:09.620 --> 00:29:14.430
of what was a very
sprawling and complex scandal.

00:29:14.430 --> 00:29:17.830
And it's also very
reassuring to journalists.

00:29:17.830 --> 00:29:20.080
It lives on because
it's a reassuring tale.

00:29:20.080 --> 00:29:24.110
It's an affirmation tale that
journalists can make a difference,

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:30.760
that they can be decisive forces
and factors in the greater scheme

00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:34.110
of things in American politics.

00:29:34.110 --> 00:29:36.410 position:56%
It's a media centric interpretation,

00:29:36.410 --> 00:29:39.700
but it's also one that's
reassuring to journalists.

00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:47.680
Let's move on to another more
recent, if you will, media myth.

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:54.230
That of the coverage of Hurricane
Katrina 12 years ago, 2005.

00:29:54.230 --> 00:29:58.320
The media themselves patted
themselves on the back saying,

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:02.050
"This was a triumph,
a media triumph."

00:30:02.050 --> 00:30:05.630
I call it the myth of
superlative reporting.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:11.380
There was a lot of self referential
praise in the immediate aftermath

00:30:11.380 --> 00:30:14.660
of the hurricane's passage.

00:30:14.660 --> 00:30:20.080
It made landfall just east of
New Orleans, and in the aftermath

00:30:20.080 --> 00:30:25.060 position:56%
