00:32:40.240 --> 00:32:43.880 position:56%
They also spoke about other horrors.

00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:47.480
Sharks plying the flood
waters of New Orleans.

00:32:47.480 --> 00:32:48.780
Things like that.

00:32:48.780 --> 00:32:53.340
This was a U.S. and an
international media response.

00:32:53.340 --> 00:32:55.610
International media,
particularly the British media,

00:32:55.610 --> 00:32:59.250
just loved this story about
the apocalypse of New Orleans.

00:32:59.250 --> 00:33:02.340
This was a moment in which
the United States was going

00:33:02.340 --> 00:33:04.270
to -- being brought down.

00:33:04.270 --> 00:33:06.810
And the British national
media just ate it up.

00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:09.170
But so did the U.S. news media.

00:33:09.170 --> 00:33:14.240
The media narrative, the dominant
media narrative, was of chaos,

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:21.270
anarchy, mayhem, and few, if
any, of these horrific accounts

00:33:21.270 --> 00:33:25.190
of lawlessness, anarchy,
and the aftermath

00:33:25.190 --> 00:33:29.480
of Hurricane Katrina's
passage were true.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:32.300
Some reporting of that
afterwards found

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:36.730
that almost all these stories
were based largely on rumor,

00:33:36.730 --> 00:33:39.690
were exaggerated, and untrue.

00:33:39.690 --> 00:33:46.830
The effects were to paint
for America and the rest

00:33:46.830 --> 00:33:51.090
of the world scenes of
unimaginable horror.

00:33:51.090 --> 00:33:55.670
And they had the effect of
defaming a city and its people

00:33:55.670 --> 00:33:58.190
at a time of their greatest need.

00:33:58.190 --> 00:34:05.290
And these misreported stories
about anarchy and chaos and mayhem

00:34:05.290 --> 00:34:09.620
in New Orleans also had the
effect of slowing the arrival

00:34:09.620 --> 00:34:16.160
of federal aid and
assistance to New Orleans.

00:34:16.160 --> 00:34:20.240
The deployment of aid was slowed
down because the situation seemed

00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:24.070
so untenable that you could
not put people in there

00:34:24.070 --> 00:34:27.480
until you were certain that
everything was under control.

00:34:27.480 --> 00:34:29.060 position:56%
These news reports in the first days

00:34:29.060 --> 00:34:33.670
after Hurricane Katrina's
passage made it clear

00:34:33.670 --> 00:34:35.780
that the situation
was not under control.

00:34:35.780 --> 00:34:38.920
In fact, it was one
of mayhem and chaos.

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:41.320
As I say, that was untrue.

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:43.810
It was largely debunked.

00:34:43.810 --> 00:34:48.660 position:56%
In fact, a bipartisan congressional
committee looking in to the response

00:34:48.660 --> 00:34:51.590
to Hurricane Katrina touched
on the media's coverage too.

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:56.300
It came to the conclusion that
if anyone rioted in the aftermath

00:34:56.300 --> 00:34:58.850
of Hurricane Katrina,
it was the media.

00:34:58.850 --> 00:35:05.350
But, as I say, chaos
was the media narrative.

00:35:05.350 --> 00:35:09.680
And I believe we have some front
pages on the display table there

00:35:09.680 --> 00:35:13.380
that suggest as much, including
the one that is on your far right

00:35:13.380 --> 00:35:16.060
from the "Times-Picayune,"
the New Orleans newspaper.

00:35:16.060 --> 00:35:17.370
"Help Us Please."

00:35:17.370 --> 00:35:20.620
The subheading read,
"After the Disaster Chaos

00:35:20.620 --> 00:35:23.300
and Lawlessness Ruled the Streets."

00:35:23.300 --> 00:35:28.850
And that, as I say, was the
dominant media narrative.

00:35:28.850 --> 00:35:33.770
So I think it's important to
keep in mind that early accounts

00:35:33.770 --> 00:35:38.460
of disasters often are in error.

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:40.780
Not always, but they often are.

00:35:40.780 --> 00:35:44.500
Hurricane Katrina was
one of those cases.

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:50.460
And it's also I think
useful to keep in mind

00:35:50.460 --> 00:35:57.090
that mainstream media are not
always going to get it right.

00:35:57.090 --> 00:35:59.290
They're not always
going to get it right.

00:35:59.290 --> 00:36:01.020
So, with that in mind, I'd

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:05.370
like to offer a few practical
straightforward suggestions

00:36:05.370 --> 00:36:10.010
that may be useful in
combating fake news.

00:36:10.010 --> 00:36:11.570
From whatever the source.

00:36:11.570 --> 00:36:13.620
From whatever the source.

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:15.270
My first suggestion --
There are five of them.

00:36:15.270 --> 00:36:20.080
My first suggestion was that
one about the mainstream media.

00:36:20.080 --> 00:36:25.060
They can get it wrong in the
early reporting about disasters.

00:36:25.060 --> 00:36:32.780
My second suggestion is develop
an ability to take the sniff test.

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:38.740
The sniff test, it's akin to when
you open the refrigerator door

00:36:38.740 --> 00:36:42.660
and the milk has gone bad.

00:36:42.660 --> 00:36:43.960
You know, you know it.

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:46.990
And it's like that
with news stories.

00:36:46.990 --> 00:36:54.890 position:56%
If something just doesn't seem quite
right, if it smells a little off,

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:56.190
then maybe you should treat it

00:36:56.190 --> 00:36:59.300
as something that's
maybe not quite accurate.

00:36:59.300 --> 00:37:04.270
Like the shooter in Las Vegas.

00:37:04.270 --> 00:37:07.150
I mean those early reports
that appeared on Facebook

00:37:07.150 --> 00:37:12.420
and Google were probably a little
too exaggerated to be true.

00:37:12.420 --> 00:37:16.830
To pass the sniff test.

00:37:16.830 --> 00:37:18.960
Be wary of sources of stories

00:37:18.960 --> 00:37:22.770
that rely exclusively
on anonymous sources.

00:37:22.770 --> 00:37:29.170
One of my favorite examples of that
is the "Washington Post's" report

00:37:29.170 --> 00:37:33.870
in early April 2003
about Jessica Lynch,

00:37:33.870 --> 00:37:40.850
a young 19 year old waif-like army
supply clerk from West Virginia

00:37:40.850 --> 00:37:45.210
who signed up for the army to be
able to use the benefits later

00:37:45.210 --> 00:37:49.760
on to go to college
and get a degree.

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:51.090
She was in a supply unit.

00:37:51.090 --> 00:37:52.970
She was in a maintenance company.

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:55.760
Never expected to see
combat in Iraq.

00:37:55.760 --> 00:38:01.260
But because of a wrong turn that
her unit took in the early days

00:38:01.260 --> 00:38:05.790
of the Iraq war, right after the
invasion began in March of 2003,

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:08.690
Jessica Lynch's unit came
under ambush in the city

00:38:08.690 --> 00:38:11.540
of Nasiriyah in southern Iraq.

00:38:11.540 --> 00:38:14.980
And the unit was badly shot up.

00:38:14.980 --> 00:38:17.610
11 people were killed in the unit.

00:38:17.610 --> 00:38:21.380
Several were taken prisoner,
among them Jessica Lynch.

00:38:21.380 --> 00:38:27.380 position:56%
She was badly injured and was
rescued by a special operations unit

00:38:27.380 --> 00:38:29.400
on the first of April, 2003.

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:32.390
It was the first time
that an American prisoner

00:38:32.390 --> 00:38:36.400
of war had been rescued from
behind enemy lines during

00:38:36.400 --> 00:38:37.700
combat operations.

00:38:37.700 --> 00:38:41.830
The first time since World War II.

00:38:41.830 --> 00:38:43.630
Two days after the rescue the

00:38:43.630 --> 00:38:47.260
"Washington Post" reports
this story on the front page.

00:38:47.260 --> 00:38:49.120
That she was fighting to the death.

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:51.610
Based on two anonymous sources.

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:53.650
And the "Post" has
never identified them.

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:57.600
Jessica Lynch was reported to
be fighting like a female Rambo,

00:38:57.600 --> 00:39:02.970
taking on the -- Attacking
Iraqis, firing her weapon

00:39:02.970 --> 00:39:06.540
until she ran out of ammunition.

00:39:06.540 --> 00:39:10.700
She kept the Iraqis at bay despite
herself being shot and stabbed

00:39:10.700 --> 00:39:13.530
and seeing colleagues
fall all around her.

00:39:13.530 --> 00:39:16.830
It was an electrifying story.

00:39:16.830 --> 00:39:20.310 position:56%
It was a story that was picked up by
news organizations around the world.

00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:25.770
It was a story that was
irresistibly good in a lot of ways.

00:39:25.770 --> 00:39:29.240
It was based on two
anonymous sources.

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:31.880
Neither of the "Post"
reporters whose bylines appeared

00:39:31.880 --> 00:39:34.270
on that story were
in Iraq at the time.

00:39:34.270 --> 00:39:36.670
They reported the story
from Washington.

00:39:36.670 --> 00:39:43.260
The story turned out to be
wrong in all important respects.

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:45.230
Jessica Lynch was in Iraq.

00:39:45.230 --> 00:39:47.110
She was in Nasiriyah with her unit.

00:39:47.110 --> 00:39:50.850
She did not fire a
shot during the ambush.

00:39:50.850 --> 00:39:53.830
Her gun jammed.

00:39:53.830 --> 00:39:56.940
And she was in the
backseat of a Humvee

00:39:56.940 --> 00:40:00.770
as it tried to escape the ambush.

00:40:00.770 --> 00:40:04.420
And she, as the Humvee was trying
to make its escape from the city --

00:40:04.420 --> 00:40:05.720
She was in the backseat
with her head

00:40:05.720 --> 00:40:07.520
down between her knees
saying, "Oh, my god.

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:08.820
Please get us out of here.

00:40:08.820 --> 00:40:10.120
Oh, my god.

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:11.500
Please get us out of here."

00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:16.120
The Humvee was struck by a rocket
propelled grenade and was thrown

00:40:16.120 --> 00:40:22.260
in to the back side of a
disabled tractor trailer truck.

00:40:22.260 --> 00:40:26.690
And Jessica Lynch was
seriously injured in that crash.

00:40:26.690 --> 00:40:29.760
She did not suffer
gunshot or stab wounds,

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:34.010
but she was badly injured
in that crash.

00:40:34.010 --> 00:40:38.870
The "Post" never explained how
it got it wrong, so badly wrong.

00:40:38.870 --> 00:40:42.190
It never discussed
who its sources were.

00:40:42.190 --> 00:40:47.180
On one occasion one of the
reporters said in an NPR interview,

00:40:47.180 --> 00:40:50.230
"Our sources for that story
were not the Pentagon.

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:52.470
They were not military sources.

00:40:52.470 --> 00:40:54.020
We could never get
anybody at the Pentagon

00:40:54.020 --> 00:40:56.600
to talk about Jessica Lynch."

00:40:56.600 --> 00:40:58.340
Which left people wondering, "Okay.

00:40:58.340 --> 00:41:00.830
Who could it have been?"

00:41:00.830 --> 00:41:02.410
Who could it have been?

00:41:02.410 --> 00:41:03.910
Anonymous sources in Washington.

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:07.550
And the town is just full of them.

00:41:07.550 --> 00:41:13.840
The point here is to be wary of
stories based on anonymous sources.

00:41:13.840 --> 00:41:15.770
Here are a few more suggestions.

